an></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ；</li><li> <i>k</i> = 1 时的正交<span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="\bf{emb\_perp}"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-texatom"><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">投影</span></span><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">e</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">m</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">b</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="margin-top: -0.291em; padding-bottom: 0.446em;">_</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">per</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">p</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">；</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li><li> <i>k</i> = 2 时的正交反射；</li><li>当<i>k</i> >; 2 时，进一步“推回”远离探测方向： </li></ul><figure class="image image_resized" style="width:79.68%"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/x6wmcttwnkth2htxvce1"><figcaption> With this approach we don&#39;t just make the embedding&#39;s cosine similarity with the probe vector negative, we can scale up the magnitude of this negative value. It approaches <strong>–</strong> 1 (the minimum possible) as <i>k</i> → <i>∞ .</i></figcaption></figure><p> At this point we start to see significant results. Running prompting experiments on randomly sampled tokens where the coefficient <i>k</i> was set to each of 0, 1, 2, 5, 8, 11, 14, 17, 20, 23, 26, 29 <span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnref3tauwmqhwgj"><sup><a href="#fn3tauwmqhwgj">[6]</a></sup></span> produced outputs like these: </p><figure class="image"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/yaa8qsw49k5tkoetn6g9" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/bdfdxjb6devrbc14k6jr 130w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/c7qsqgsmpv83icxvszba 260w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/unouc5fmwylocf4ulgmw 390w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/hizp8vhp3xgjytglauer 520w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/uzdfirdorydjdfxi7bhx 650w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/nnuwcxzebekc9ypkan2t 780w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/lp78ihzxfmjvlimxahjb 910w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/ukligcebcugcmyyhhduy 1040w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/po91gvy9porukh1fvjrx 1170w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/l9ejj6npzc8ksnrqar4l 1232w"></figure><p> We see that mutating the &#39; neg&#39; token embedding by orthogonal reflection across the &#39;N&#39;-probe&#39;s orthogonal complement (ie, using <i>k</i> = 2) does not change the correct first letter prediction, but if we push the embedding back further by increasing <i>k</i> to 5,  GPT-J switches its prediction to &#39;E&#39;, the second letter. Likewise, mutating the &#39; administration&#39; token embedding with <i>k</i> = 11 switches the prediction from &#39;A&#39; to &#39;D&#39; and mutating the &#39;han&#39; embedding with <i>k</i> = 14 switches the prediction to &#39;A&#39;. The token &#39; hatred&#39; is an example of the 25.2% of tokens for which GPT-J switches its prediction of the first letter as soon as <i>k</i> = 2 (and one of the 10.3% where it switches to predicting the actual second letter of the token).</p><p> We can see that in the case of &#39; racial&#39;, when <i>k</i> = 8 the first letter prediction becomes &#39;C&#39;, the <i>third</i> letter. For &#39; car&#39; we have to increase <i>k</i> to 17 to switch the prediction, at which it becomes &#39;R&#39;, again the third letter.</p><p> The first letter prediction for &#39; contact&#39; stays &#39;C&#39; across the range of <i>k</i> values tested for. For &#39; losing&#39;, the first change occurs at <i>k</i> = 17 where we get &#39;C&#39;, a letter extraneous to the token.</p><p> It seems that for sufficiently large values of the coefficient <i>k</i> , we can push back a token embedding in the opposite direction of the relevant probe vector and cause GPT-J prompt outputs to mis-predict the first letter. The necessary value of <i>k</i> varies from token to token, and usually exceeds what is necessary for the probe-based method to begin mis-predicting the token&#39;s first letter.<br></p><h3> Probe-based prediction after pushback with <i>k</i> = 5</h3><p> Looking at probe-based predictions on the entire set of all-Roman tokens after applying the geometric &quot;pushback&quot; transformation with <i>k</i> = 5, we find that only 0.5% of tokens having their first letter correctly predicted now (bear in mind that random guessing would score ~4%). Pushing back that far and thereby approaching minimum possible cosine similarity with the relevant first-letter probe vector seems to almost guarantee that the model will <i>not</i> predict the correct first letter. Its mis-predictions for the first letters of tokens distribute like this: </p><figure class="image image_resized" style="width:81.67%"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/wqnb6hzaygxj0fjlzx6n" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/blz9n9iz6hwx3ivtoyqx 100w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/vioz3i4pngcpzqyqmnc7 200w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/lu497jeyis5izhsq9oij 300w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/iyojlya5ecdibubxedrq 400w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/eq8dobq5snh4ehumet1m 500w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/ec35pkszp1j06c7bxe37 600w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/hk3cbcz2kwp5r0uoqzlk 700w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/ebbznrhmahutipxhszoq 800w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/hxwkmd1klgbdjk5hpe2t 900w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/pylwdn2xohgq7mzn1mhw 989w"></figure><p> The probability of an extraneous letter being predicted by the probe method has remained at 44% (as it was for <i>k</i> = 2), and again we see a similar rate of decay for subsequently positioned letters matching the mis-prediction, with the second letter matching it in 52% of these cases.<br></p><h3> Prompt-based predictions as <i>k</i> varies</h3><p> The following bar chart shows results for 1052 tokens (sampled randomly from the subset of all-Roman tokens), where GPT-J prompts were run on pushed-back embeddings <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="\mathbf{emb^*}"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-texatom"><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">e</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">m</span></span> <span class="mjx-msubsup"><span class="mjx-base"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">b</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-sup" style="font-size: 70.7%; vertical-align: 0.513em; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0.071em;"><span class="mjx-mo" style=""><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-B" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for <i>k</i> values 0, 1, 2, 5, 8, 11, 14, 17, 20, 23, 26 and 29. Again, the 2-shot prompt template was this:</p><pre> <code>The string &quot; heaven&quot; begins with the letter &quot;H&quot; The string &quot; same&quot; begins with the letter &quot;S&quot; The string &quot;&lt;emb*>;&quot; begins with the letter &quot;</code></pre><p> We see that for ~42% of these tokens, at the smallest tested <i>k</i> value for which GPT-J switches first-letter prediction (ie where the green rectangles turn red in the diagram above), the new prediction matches the token&#39;s second letter. The drop-off for letters deeper into the token string follows the same kind of decay curve we&#39;ve seen for both prompt- and probe-based predictions, roughly halving with each subsequent letter position. For only 14% of the tokens, the new prediction is a letter extraneous to the token (the column labelled &quot;–1&quot;). </p><figure class="image image_resized" style="width:86.49%"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/sepshtrfx4sm4zi1l3fp"><figcaption> Switched to 2nd letter: 41.7%;  3rd letter: 24.3%; 4th letter: 10.7%; 5th letter:  5.4%;<br> 6th letter: 2%; 7th letter: 1.1%; 8th letter: 0.4%; letter extraneous to token: 13.7%</figcaption></figure><p> Further bar charts were produced from the same data, but counting &quot;switch letter positions&quot; for specific (rather than all) <i>k</i> values. These all showed the same kind of decay curve. Here&#39;s the chart for <i>k</i> = 5: </p><figure class="image image_resized" style="width:89.5%"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/yrs7vhd6xjdtsdggybgh"><figcaption> Having collected all the tokens where GPT-J first switches its first letter prediction when <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="2 < k \leq 5"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mn"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">2</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo MJXc-space3"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">&lt;</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi MJXc-space3"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">k</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo MJXc-space3"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.446em;">≤</span></span> <span class="mjx-mn MJXc-space3"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">5</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> <span><span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label=""><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"></span></span></span></span></span> , this counts for how many it switches to the second letter, third letter, etc.</figcaption></figure><p><br> The following histogram shows the smallest <i>k</i> coefficient at which GPT-J ceases to predict the correct first letter (the bin marked &quot;–1&quot; counts those tokens where no switch was observed, ie the correct first letter continues to be predicted up to <i>k</i> = 29).  In simplest terms, this can be thought of as showing &quot;how far you have to &#39;push back&#39; token embeddings to blind GPT-J to their first letter&quot;: </p><figure class="image"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/fif9eut1hhhgrmqsqrrj" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/elxqqoj5tpygd8btv5a6 100w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/myfgpiljnuav9msuzjtu 200w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/wh3lraelag9m0v3diteh 300w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/w4zyl30e7hfk2vpfqfyn 400w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/bjer2ezvcu37aa3mzsjj 500w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/l9l6uovsyl35fu7iygp5 600w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/lg1hgk0teke0r8ztrmjp 700w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/GyaDCzsyQgc48j8t3/y5jf2veqyqctqd3mxq38 800w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/G